          </div>
          <div class="arup-call-tile arup-call-tile-fake">
            <div class="arup-call-tile-scanline"></div>
            <span class="arup-call-tile-icon" aria-hidden="true">👤</span>
            <span class="arup-call-tile-label">Colleague</span>
            <span class="arup-call-tile-role">UK Operations</span>
          </div>
          <div class="arup-call-tile arup-call-tile-fake">
            <div class="arup-call-tile-scanline"></div>
            <span class="arup-call-tile-icon" aria-hidden="true">👤</span>
            <span class="arup-call-tile-label">Colleague</span>
            <span class="arup-call-tile-role">Finance</span>
          </div>
          <div class="arup-call-tile arup-call-tile-real">
            <span class="arup-call-tile-icon" aria-hidden="true">🟢</span>
            <span class="arup-call-tile-label">You</span>
            <span class="arup-call-tile-role">HK Finance</span>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="arup-call-footer">
          <div class="arup-call-quote">
            "(In the) multi-person video conference, it turns out that everyone [he saw] was fake."
            <cite>— Baron Chan Shun-ching, Hong Kong Police</cite>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <p class="arup-call-context">Participant count approximate. Sources describe "multiple" and "several" colleagues plus the CFO. No source names the video platform used.</p>

      <p>The call worked. The employee's phishing suspicions dissolved. He had done what the training told him to do — verify visually — and what he saw confirmed the request was genuine.</p>
      <p>Over the course of approximately one week in January 2024, the employee executed 15 transfers totaling HK$200 million — approximately US$25.6 million — to five Hong Kong bank accounts.</p>

